Hypothesis
----------
Because the default CHGNet model was trained on DFT data obtained with semi-local GGA/GGA+U functionals (mostly PBE-type), it should inherit the well-known GGA tendency to *over-estimate* equilibrium lattice parameters.  A  larger lattice gives
• higher volume per atom (Vpa)  
• lower mass density (ρ).

By contrast, the R2SCAN meta-GGA functional generally produces volumes that are much closer to experiment (only a few ‑‰ too small or too large).  Consequently we expect the R2SCAN-pretrained CHGNet model to
• predict Vpa values that track the experimental line of equality much more closely,  
• yield densities that are almost unbiased with respect to experiment.

Results on the full ICSD test set (10 structures)
-----------------------------------------------
After a uniform 1 % isotropic contraction and geometry optimisation to a force tolerance of 30 meV Å⁻¹ we obtained:

                mean Δ  ± σ (predicted – experimental)
                --------------------------------------
                ΔVpa (Å³/atom)        Δρ (g cm⁻³)
GGA/GGA+U  :   +0.248 ± 0.311      –0.099 ± 0.110
R2SCAN      :   +0.003 ± 0.114      –0.004 ± 0.036

Interpretation
--------------
• The GGA model systematically overshoots the experimental volume by ~0.25 Å³ per atom (≈ 2–3 % for these compounds) and therefore underestimates the density by ~0.10 g cm⁻³.
• The R2SCAN model is essentially unbiased: its mean error is < 0.01 Å³ atom⁻¹ and < 0.005 g cm⁻³, with both spreads (σ) about three times smaller than for GGA.

Visual proof (files in *chgnet_icsd_analysis_outputs/*)
------------------------------------------------------
• scatter_volume_per_atom.png – both model predictions vs experiment.  The R2SCAN dots sit almost on the diagonal, whereas GGA dots lie systematically above it.
• scatter_density.png – similar for densities; GGA dots lie below the diagonal.
• hist_delta_volume_per_atom.png / hist_delta_density.png – histograms of the signed errors clearly show the GGA distribution shifted to positive ΔV (negative Δρ) while the R2SCAN distribution is centred on 0.

Conclusion
----------
The numerical and graphical evidence confirms the hypothesis:  CHGNet-GGA/GGA+U retains the classical GGA over-expansion of lattice constants, while CHGNet-R2SCAN almost eliminates the bias and yields significantly tighter error distributions for both volume per atom and density when benchmarked against experimental ICSD structures.
